<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-619-117  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 619 117.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Nov 1990 v112 n5 p73(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>User interfaces are getting easier.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Saito, Taiji.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fax is now the most popular way to send document communication,due to the simplicity of the equipment and the ease-of-use.andO;However, users want more sophistication together with thissimplicity, such as memory, large autodialers on fax machines,document editing and finishing capabilities on copiers.andP;  To bridgethe gap, graphic interfaces and pull-down menus are employed.andO;Other users are using 'gap-bridging' interface technologies onstand-alone office products.andP;  Users operate machines by scanningbar codes, filling out menu cards and touching computer screens.andO;Speech recognition is another technology that offers more accessto computers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FacsimileProduct DevelopmentVoice CommunicationsInterfaceScanningUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>